text_blocks.snippet: Frank Sinatra died in 1998 at the age of 82. If he were alive today, February 7, 2026, he would be 110 years old.
Sinatra was a multi-faceted entertainer who held several professional roles throughout his 60-year career:

list.snippet: Occupations: Singer (Crooner), Actor, Film Producer, Director, and Record Label Founder (Reprise Records).
Vocal Delivery & Phrasing: Known for a meticulous, "instrumental" approach to phrasing, often singing long lines without breaking for breath.
Emotional Interpretation: Exceptional at conveying the specific narrative and emotion of lyrics.
Studio Microphone Technique: Pioneered using the microphone as an instrument to create intimacy or power.
Conducting/Arranging: Collaborated deeply with arrangers like Nelson Riddle to define the "concept album".

text_blocks.snippet: Sinatra is widely regarded as one of the most proficient and influential vocalists in history.

list.snippet: Technical Proficiency: He possessed perfect pitch and a vocal range approaching a bass-baritone. Although he never learned to read music, he had a "monster" musical ear and was a perfectionist who often did dozens of takes to reach his standard.
Awards: His mastery is evidenced by 11 Grammy Awards (including Legend and Lifetime Achievement awards) and an Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor.

text_blocks.snippet: At the time of his death in 1998, Sinatra's primary residence was in Los Angeles, California. He passed away at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles. His final resting place is Desert Memorial Park in Cathedral City, California.
